post_text:
A message from Superintendent, Brian Pearson

GCS Parents:

Thank you for your patience and support as we work through the challenges of returning to school. Overall, this first week was a success: 80% of our students were back on campus and 20% were engaged in our new distance platform. We do recognize that the changes in building schedules and protocols this year have led to some increased traffic issues, especially at the east end of town. Although there is no easy fix for this problem, we are confident that we can make the issues more manageable. We are working on opening up a morning latchkey program at GIS, NOE, and SME that should help to stagger the drop off times and reduce traffic congestion. Our transportation department is also working with the city police department to explore traffic patterns and possible route changes. I am confident that we can take steps to reduce parent wait time and increase safety. I appreciate you working with us as we address these important issues.

Gaylord Middle School Football Information:

Per the Governor's new executive order, MHSAA is now allowing football to be played again. Gaylord Middle School will start practice on Thursday, 9-10-2020 right after school until 5PM at the GIS field. If students had a physical on file at the school last year that will count for this year but will still need to fill out the MHSAA Health Questionnaire:

https://www.gaylordschools.com/downloads/high_school_files/mhsaa_health_questionnaire.pdf.

If they do not have a physical on file with the GMS office they will need one in order to participate.

All equipment is provided to students. The first game will be on 9-23-20.

We will be following the MHSAA guidelines for football:
https://www.mhsaa.com/portals/0/Documents/AD%20Forms/PACKET%20FB.pdf

shared_text:
Gaylord Athletics
September 1 at 2:07 PM ·

Gaylord Athletics is pleased to announce that with the help of Brian Gerstenberger and the E-Free Church, Gaylord High School will be live streaming our 2020-21 Volleyball Matches that are held at Gaylord HS. Under Governor Whitmer’s current executive order, attendance is reduced at all indoor volleyball matches. By live streaming the games, we hope that volleyball fans that are not able to attend will be able to still watch the action.
The first live streamed match will take place on Wednesday Sept 2 as the Blue Devils take on Alpena which will be live streamed on the Gaylord Athletics Facebook Page. The JV match will begin live streaming at 5:00 pm while the Varsity match will begin live streaming at approximately 6:30 pm. The Freshman match will also be shown on a tape delay and be posted on the Gaylord Athletics Facebook Page by the following morning.

Kids Read Now summer reading program us is in full swing for elementary students! Parents of students finishing Kindergarten – 3rd grade please be sure to report the books that you receive from Kids Read Now. Directions on how to report each book is on the inside cover of each book. If you have not received your first book please contact Kids Read Now at 877.536.0130 or your classroom teacher. We want to be sure EVERY child is able to participate this summer.

A virtual kick off to the summer reading program has put together since we can’t be together. The video will explain Kids Read Now, why it is important and how to report books so that you continue to receive books. Please take a minute to watch it. https://www.schooltube.com/media/2020+Kids+Read+Now+Virtual+Family+Reading+Event/1_kt9ml8al

So far, we have 182 books reported to Kids Read Now. Kindergarten has reported the most! A shout out to Mrs. Wansa’s class and Mrs. Massey’s class for the most books reported per class. Keep reading boys and girls!

post_text:
Gaylord Community Schools Families,

I wanted to thank you all for completing and returning the survey that was distributed last Thursday regarding technology within your homes. The data in the survey is helping us prepare a platform to be able to continue to provide an education to your children during this time of school closure. Currently we are building an online delivery system so that instruction can reach each and every student through their own teachers. We are also making preparations for students that do not have access to the internet or a device at home. We are working very hard to develop an effective and engaging program.

Our plan is to be able to implement the program beginning on April 6 if the school closure gets extended. We will not be providing this program before that due to the complexity of the design and staff training.

Please check the Gaylord Community Schools website as well as the Facebook page for updates.

Thanks,

Dennis Keck
Director of Special Education and Curriculum

The Gaylord Blue Devil Wellness Center will remain open during the March 16 - April 5 shutdown continuing to offer both mental and physical health services. Please use the entrance at the Southwest corner of the High School.

In order to best serve each client and reduce the risk for the spread of illness, please contact the center for an appointment so we can ensure limited contact in waiting rooms. If you have any questions or would like to make an appointment, please contact us at (989) 732-6890.

Thanks and stay healthy!

post_text:
A message from E-Free Church:

E-Free Church would like to bless our community during this time of uncertainty. Due to cancelling our Men's Conference we will have over 800 individually wrapped Panera Bread sandwiches that will be available free of charge on Saturday, March 14, from 11:30am-1:30pm, or until they are gone.

If the effects of our current state of emergency are going to cause hardship to your family, we hope this will help. Sandwiches will be available under the overhang of the main church entrance. If you know someone who is in need, please feel free to come pick up sandwiches and deliver them.

post_text: Today Mrs. Brand’s first graders at North Ohio were treated to a wonderful gift of love and kindness. Nana Sparks (the mother of Kim Hattis, NOE Instructional Assistant) brought in goody bags for every student filled with all kinds of goodness. Each student received a beautiful handmade knitted blanket, new socks, a new toothbrush/toothpaste, and lots of treats! Students were literally wrapped up in love today! Thank you so much to Nana Sparks (Cheryl Sparks) and her knitting friends! We will remember this day forever!

post_text: Business Computer Technology students’ in Mrs. Florian’s class have been studying Entrepreneurship. After learning what it takes to be a successful entrepreneur they found Kim Daisy, Founder of Daisy Cakes. Kim has been on Shark Tank, The Today Show and Good Morning America (and many more) showcasing her amazing cakes that she creates using her Grandma’s recipes. The students discovered that if you put your mind into something, you can create it.
